{"parse":{"title":"Q-based narrowing","pageid":7616828,"revid":791847024,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In the framework of <a href=\"/wiki/Yale\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Yale\">Yale</a> linguist <a href=\"/wiki/Laurence_Horn\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Laurence Horn\">Laurence Horn</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Neo-Gricean\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Neo-Gricean\">Neo-Gricean</a> approach to <a href=\"/wiki/Semantics\" title=\"Semantics\">semantics</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Pragmatics\" title=\"Pragmatics\">pragmatics</a>,  <b>Q-based narrowing</b> or a \"Q-based implicature\" is an inference that results from application of the <a href=\"/wiki/Q-Principle\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Q-Principle\">Q-Principle</a> \"Say as much as you can [given R],\" as it interacts with the <a href=\"/wiki/R-Principle\" title=\"R-Principle\">R-Principle</a> \"Say no more than you must [given Q].\" <sup id=\"cite_ref-SEP_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SEP-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A Q-based inference is built around the assumption that if the speaker did not make a stronger statement (or say more), then its denial is (implied to be) true. For instance, the inference from \"He entered a house\" to \"He did not enter his own house\" is Q-based inference, i.e. deriving from the Q-Principle. <sup id=\"cite_ref-SEP_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SEP-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Q-based_narrowing&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Linguistics_stub.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Linguistics_stub.svg/40px-Linguistics_stub.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"17\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Linguistics_stub.svg/60px-Linguistics_stub.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Linguistics_stub.svg/80px-Linguistics_stub.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"175\" data-file-height=\"74\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Semantics\" title=\"Semantics\">semantics</a> article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Q-based_narrowing&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Semantics-stub\" title=\"Template:Semantics-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Semantics-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Semantics-stub\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Semantics-stub&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table><div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-SEP-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-SEP_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SEP_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/implicature/\">\"Implicature\"</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Stanford_Encyclopedia_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy\">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a> The <a href=\"/wiki/Q-Principle\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Q-Principle\">Q-Principle</a> is a reformulation of Grice's Maxim of Quantity (<i>see</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Gricean_maxims\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gricean maxims\">Gricean maxims</a>) combining with it Grice's first two submaxims of Manner.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1277\nCached time: 20180907175444\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.044 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.066 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 60/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 2650/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 0/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 3/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 186/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.011/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 784 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   38.526      1 Template:Semantics-stub\n100.00%   38.526      1 -total\n 94.30%   36.328      1 Template:Asbox\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:7616828-0!canonical and timestamp 20180907175444 and revision id 791847024\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"All_stub_articles"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Semiotics_stubs"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Linguistics_stubs"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Semantics"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Pragmatics"}],"links":[{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Semantics-stub"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Gricean maxims"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Laurence Horn"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Neo-Gricean"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Pragmatics"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Q-Principle"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"R-Principle"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Semantics"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Yale"},{"ns":4,"exists":"","*":"Wikipedia:Stub"},{"ns":11,"exists":"","*":"Template talk:Semantics-stub"}],"templates":[{"ns":10